ntellectual spectrum of Muslim thought over the globe. Handbook attempts to find answers to some questions concerning the definition and characteristics of the ethical system in Islam. What is its goal and how do its rules and practices ensure welfare for individuals and society? Are the moral principles universal and invariable or do they change and adapt with the social changes of communities and progress in science and technology? Is the present generation accountable for the welfare of future generations? Where is the boundary between law and ethics and who guarantees their adoption and implementation?  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEconomicsxMoral and ethical aspectszIslamic countries. 0aEconomicsxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aFinancexMoral and ethical aspectszIslamic countries. 0aFinancexReligious aspectsxIslam. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Business Ethics.2bisacsh  aEthics.  aIslamic Finance.  aMorality.  aSpirituality.  aTrust.1 aAbedi Jafari, Hassan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAkram Laldin, Mohamad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChanna, Bilal S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsma’eil Tavassoli, Mohammad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEzzati, Morteza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarahanifard, Mohammad Ali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarahanifard, Saeed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Omar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHabibian Naghibi, Majid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHossein Nasr, Seyyed, econtributor.4ct